To prevent Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, you should always sanitize and escape user input before displaying it in the response. One common approach is to use OWASP's ESAPI library for Java to handle input validation and output encoding.

Here's an updated version of the code snippet that properly sanitizes the user input using ESAPI library:

```java
import java.io.*;
import javax.servlet.*;
import javax.servlet.http.*;
import org.owasp.esapi.ESAPI;
import org.owasp.esapi.codecs.HTMLEntityCodec;

public class XSSDemoServlet extends HttpServlet {
    protected void doPost(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response) throws ServletException, IOException {
        String userInput = request.getParameter("input");
        PrintWriter out = response.getWriter();

        out.println("<html>");
        out.println("<head><title>XSS Demo</title></head>");
        out.println("<body>");

        // Sanitize and encode user input before displaying
        HTMLEntityCodec codec = new HTMLEntityCodec();
        String sanitizedInput = codec.encode(userInput);

        out.println("<h1>User Input: " + sanitizedInput + "</h1>");

        out.println("</body>");
        out.println("</html>");
    }
}

### Explanation:
취약유형: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
